  "market_context": "Bearish market structure on 15-minute chart with lower highs/lower lows since prior swing high; New York session opening after London session equal highs formed a liquidity pocket; 1-minute timeframe initially bullish but shifted bearish after liquidity sweep.",
  "key_observation": "Price swept London session equal highs (liquidity) and then the 1-minute structure shifted from bullish to bearish, confirming alignment with the bearish 15-minute trend and triggering a short entry at an inverted FVG/Order Block zone.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the 15-minute market structure as bearish via lower high → lower low sequence (Change of Character), establishing swing high at highest pullback point and swing low at London session lows.",
    "Step 2: Recognize London session equal highs as a pocket of SSL (Sell Side Liquidity) — a confluence zone where price often reverses after sweep.",
    "Step 3: Monitor 1-minute timeframe for structural confirmation: initially bullish (higher high, equal lows), but after sweeping liquidity, price broke the 1-minute low, shifting structure to bearish.",
    "Step 4: Locate entry zone at the inverted fair value gap (bearish FVG formed after bullish FVG was traded through) and adjacent supply order block near 1.1330–1.1338.",
    "Step 5: Place stop loss above the recent 1-minute high (invalidation level), and set target at the 15-minute swing low for 1:6 risk-reward."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade executed short at ~1.1332, stop loss above 1.1338, target at 15-minute swing low (~1.1275); price reached target, achieving ~1:6 R:R.",
  "lessons": "Trade only when higher-timeframe bias and lower-timeframe confirmation align; liquidity sweeps into key structural levels (e.g., equal highs) often precede continuation; entry at imbalanced zones (FVG/OB) improves probability.",
